  "metadata": [
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Summary"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "Project STORMFURY was a joint effort by NOAA and the Department of Defense to research hurricane modification through cloud seeding with silver iodide. Conducted over the Gulf of Mexico, Caribbean Sea, and southwestern North Atlantic, the project aimed to reduce hurricane intensity by releasing silver iodide into storm clouds. The goal was to lessen hurricane damage, which costs millions annually. While the project promised potential benefits, concerns included possible environmental impacts, such as changes in precipitation patterns and effects on marine life. The project was seen as a step towards understanding and potentially controlling hurricanes."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Themes"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "Climate and Weather Modification"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Main Location"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "Gulf of Mexico, Caribbean Sea, and southwestern North Atlantic"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Key People"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration",
          "Department of Defense",
          "Governor of Florida Reubin Askew",
          "Governor of Texas Preston Smith",
          "U.S. Department of the Interior"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Historical Context"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "Project STORMFURY was proposed in response to the devastating impacts of hurricanes, which caused significant economic damage each year. While the idea of modifying hurricanes through cloud seeding was innovative, it faced public and scientific skepticism regarding its effectiveness and potential environmental consequences. Ultimately, the project was conducted in the 1960s and 1970s but did not lead to successful hurricane modification and was eventually discontinued."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Completed"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "Completed"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "label": {
        "none": [
          "Notable Quotes"
        ]
      },
      "value": {
        "none": [
          "\"Hurricane modification, which may reduce rainfall and subsequently the fresh water flow into the coastal zone, could be damaging to fish and wildlife values. Conversely, hurricane modification which reduces the immensely destructive winds would be beneficial.\" — Jack O. Horton, Deputy Assistant Secretary of the Interior",
          "\"The State of Texas appreciates this opportunity to comment on and endorse the Project STORMFURY experiments.\" — Governor of Texas Preston Smith"
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
